40|$|Arikara Medicine Ceremony- The Buffalo Dancing. Captioned "Arikara Medicine Ceremony- The Buffalo Dancing" and "From Copyright Photograph 1908 by E. S. Curtis". In the {{foreground}} up close, {{a line of}} three Arikara men can be seen walking wearing loincloths, moccasins, scarves, necklaces, braids, shawls, and other ornaments. They can be seen holding rattles, <b>buffalo</b> <b>skins,</b> and feathers. In {{the foreground}} to the left, a tree is visible with its trunk decorated. In the background, to the left, in the distance, tipis are visible...|$|R
5000|$|In the 1580s, {{two small}} Spanish expeditions, that of Chamuscado and Rodriguez and the later Antonio de Espejo, passed through La Junta. They {{reported}} that the men were “handsome” and the women “beautiful,” although “naked and barbarous people.” [...] The Indians lived in low, flat-roofed houses; grew corn, squash and beans; and hunted and fished along the river. They gave the Spaniards well-tanned deer and <b>buffalo</b> <b>skins.</b> The expeditions' descriptions of La Junta indicated a more settled agricultural people than those described 50 years earlier by Cabeza de Vaca.|$|R
60|$|On the day {{following}} the murder, {{a band of}} Indians arrived at Fort Erie with <b>buffalo</b> <b>skins</b> for sale. To the amazement of every one Darkeye himself was among them. The wily savage--knowing that his attempting to quit {{that part of the}} country as a fugitive would be certain to fix suspicion on him as the murderer--resolved to face the fur-traders as if he were ignorant of the deed which had been done. By the very boldness of this step he hoped to disarm suspicion; but he forgot the bitten ball.|$|R
